To compare two integers in JavaScript and output the result, you can use relational operators such as `>`, `<`, `>=`, `<=`, `===`, and `!==`. Here's a simple example demonstrating how to compare two integers and output the result:

```javascript
// Declare two integer variables
let integer1 = 10;
let integer2 = 20;

// Compare the integers and output the result
if (integer1 > integer2) {
    console.log(`${integer1} is greater than ${integer2}`);
} else if (integer1 < integer2) {
    console.log(`${integer1} is less than ${integer2}`);
} else if (integer1 === integer2) {
    console.log(`${integer1} is equal to ${integer2}`);
}

// Additionally, you can compare using other operators
if (integer1 >= integer2) {
    console.log(`${integer1} is greater than or equal to ${integer2}`);
}

if (integer1 <= integer2) {
    console.log(`${integer1} is less than or equal to ${integer2}`);
}

if (integer1 !== integer2) {
    console.log(`${integer1} is not equal to ${integer2}`);
}
```

This code snippet compares two integers and outputs the result of each comparison using the appropriate relational operators. You can modify the values of `integer1` and `integer2` to test different scenarios.
